[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(3) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Grace . . . and peace.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—See Note on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 1:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "God the Father.—We may see by this verse how the title “Father,” originally used in the present formula to distinguish between the Divine Persons, came gradually to contract a wider signification. God is, through Christ, the Father of all who by their relation to Christ are admitted into the position of “sons” (Romans 8:14-17; Galatians 4:5-7). Hence, where no special limitation is imposed by the context, this secondary sense may be taken as included.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "God the Father.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—We may see by this verse how the title “Father,” originally used in the present formula to distinguish between the Divine Persons, came gradually to contract a wider signification. God is, through Christ, the Father of all who by their relation to Christ are admitted into the position of “sons” (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Romans 8:14-17",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Galatians 4:5-7",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "). Hence, where no special limitation is imposed by the context, this secondary sense may be taken as included.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And from our Lord Jesus Christ.—Strictly, it would be more in accordance with the theology of St. Paul to say that grace and peace were given from the Father, by, or through, the Son. Here the one preposition from is used to cover both cases, just as by had been used in Galatians 1:1. It is equally correct to use the word “from” with reference to a mediate and to the ultimate stage in the act of procession. Water may be drawn not only from the fountain-head, but also from the running stream.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "And from our Lord Jesus Christ.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Strictly, it would be more in accordance with the theology of St. Paul to say that grace and peace were given ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "from",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " the Father, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "by,",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " or ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "through,",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " the Son. Here the one preposition ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "from",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " is used to cover both cases, just as ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "by",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " had been used in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Galatians 1:1",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". It is equally correct to use the word “from” with reference to a mediate and to the ultimate stage in the act of procession. Water may be drawn not only from the fountain-head, but also from the running stream.",
            "children": []
