  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 3.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Grace be to you and peace",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "χάρις",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ὑμῖν καὶ εἰρήνη",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "grace to you and peace.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Here, as often, we have combined the form of salutation prevalent among Greeks, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "χαίρειν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (found in its unaltered form in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "James 1:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"wishing joy\"), Christianized into ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "χάρις",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", grace, which denotes the outpouring of Divine benignity in all such spiritual blessings as sinful creatures need; and the Hebrew greeting, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "shalom",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which in its transformation into ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "εἰρήνη",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " may be supposed to have dropped in its Christianized signification some of its originally comprehensive meaning, which comprised all \"health and wealth\" as well as \"peace,\" and to have generally expressed the more limited idea of that calm sense of reconciliation and that perfect security against evil which constitute the peculiar happiness of a soul which believes in Christ. It is nevertheless conceivable that ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "εἰρήνη",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", as used in Hellenistic Greek, may at times have widened the sense proper to it in ordinary Greek into the more comprehensive import of the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "shalom",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which it was regularly employed to represent. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "From God the Father, and from our Lord Jesus Christ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἀπὸ Θεοῦ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "πατρός καὶ Κυρίου ἡμῶν Ἰησοῦ Ξριστοῦ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). These words regularly form a part in the apostle's formula of greeting. With slight variations they are found in all his Epistles, except, perhaps, the First to the Thessalonians, where, though read in the Textus Receptus, they are omitted by recent editors. \"Our\" is added to \"Father\" in at least seven of St. Paul's Epistles (Romans, 1 and 2 Corinthians, Ephesians, Philippians, Colossians, Philemon). This warrants the belief that, when as in 1 Timothy, Titus, and here, he wrote \"God the Father,\" he most probably did so with reference to God's fatherly relation to the members of Christ's Church. Tregelles and the margin of the revised Greek text, in fact, read ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἡμῶν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
