      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἀπό",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), before the two names, \"God\" and \"Jesus Christ;\" as in the first verse in this Epistle there is only one preposition, \"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "through",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",\" before \"Jesus Christ\" and \"God.\" The apostle, looking upwards, discerns, as St. Stephen did, in the ineffable glory, the supreme God in whom he recognizes \"our Father,\" and with him Jesus Christ, \"our Lord;\" that is, our Master, Head, Mediator, \"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "through",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " whom are all things, and we through him.\" Grace and peace coming down from heaven, must come ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "from",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " God our Father ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "and",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Jesus Christ our Lord. From the very nature of the case it is obvious that the blessings referred to come to us ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "through",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Christ, though also \"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "from\"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " him; as also that St. Paul's delegation as apostle, spoken of in the first verse, originated ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "from",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " a volition and appointment of God the Father, as well as was brought about \"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "through\"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the ordering of his providence. But in each case the preposition used by the apostle preserves its proper force, not to be confused by our thrusting into it another notion not just then in the writer's view. Galatians 1:3",
